(engineering-doc
  :name "Composer 2.0 — Cross-Surface + Accessibility Design"
  :version "2.0"
  :date "2026-07-17"
  :audience "Motoi + Sakura runtime teams; Curator canvas team; Book of Composer authors; accessibility reviewers"
  :status "design-proposal-for-alfred-review"
  :authored-by "Lacuna Engineering, research + design lane"
  :supersedes-in-part "COMPOSER-1.0 (verb surface stands; this doc extends the RENDERING surface)"
  :provenance
    (:asked-by "Alfred"
     :ask "Give me a good design from Lacuna that solves the issues of PICO-8 and TIC-80 — cross-surface (desktop / iPad / phone / terminal / web) + accessibility."
     :date "2026-07-17"
     :composes-with "COMPOSER-1.0 (verb layer), LLM-AUGMENTED-REPL-1.0 (any-surface-renders-it doctrine), HELLO-SURFACE-1.0 (hydration layer), KID-FROM-NORTH-GEORGIA (the WHY)")

  :doctrine
"# The whole point

PICO-8 and TIC-80 built beautiful desktop composers and then treated every non-desktop surface as afterthought. The iPad kid, the phone kid, the Chromebook kid, and the blind kid all get half-tools or no tools. That is a doctrine failure, not a bug list.

Composer 2.0 inverts the priority: **every widget verb ships with a RENDERER FAMILY, not a single renderer.** The desktop canvas is one renderer among seven. The verb doesn't know or care which one is drawing it.

Non-negotiable properties (all inherited from COMPOSER-1.0 and re-affirmed here):

  1. **The output is readable Scheme.** No surface may add binary blobs, per-device state, or lossy exports.
  2. **The round-trip is lossless ACROSS SURFACES.** A sprite started on desktop, tweaked on phone, and played on iPad is the same `.slat` file every step. No conversion. No 'mobile version.'
  3. **Every renderer degrades honestly.** If a surface cannot render a widget (e.g., a piano-roll on a 4-line terminal), it says so and offers a fallback verb the user can call. It does NOT silently drop the widget.
  4. **Accessibility is a renderer family, not a checkbox.** Screen-reader, high-contrast, low-vision, switch-access, voice — each is a first-class renderer, not a retrofit."

  :diagnostic-table
"# What PICO-8 and TIC-80 get wrong cross-surface

| # | Failure                              | Where it hurts                              | PICO-8 status                            | TIC-80 status                            | Composer 2.0 answer                                          |
|---|--------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
| 1 | No official iPad app                 | Kid on iPad can't compose at all            | Pocket8 is playback-only, sideloaded     | No native iOS composer                   | iPad renderer family — touch-first widgets, no sideload      |
| 2 | Mobile web keyboard broken           | Can't type into editor on phone/tablet      | N/A (no web IDE)                         | Spacebar scrolls, Ctrl/Ret/Esc drop     | Widget renderer bypasses text-entry for common ops           |
| 3 | Touch not treated as clicks          | Even played carts don't respond on phones   | Aftermarket wrappers                     | Confirmed bug (issue #685)               | Every widget carries a :touch handler as first-class         |
| 4 | Screen-reader is aftermarket         | Blind kid gets nothing without pico-a11y    | Community template (set_sr_text)         | Nothing native                           | Screen-reader renderer family — every widget has :aria       |
| 5 | Fine motor: 8x8 sprite on fingertip  | Can't draw a single pixel accurately        | Not addressed                            | Not addressed                            | Sprite-grid renderer swaps to zoom+pan+lasso on touch        |
| 6 | No voice input                       | Motor-impaired kid excluded entirely        | Not addressed                            | Not addressed                            | Voice renderer family — every widget has :speech grammar     |
| 7 | Multi-device state is manual         | Copy file, hope for the best                | Cart file over Splore, manual            | Cart file, manual                        | Local-first sync via CRDT-friendly .slat + Cortex session    |
| 8 | Offline is accidental                | Chromebook loses wifi mid-lesson => lost    | Desktop-only, so 'offline' by default    | Web IDE breaks offline                   | Local-first by design; sync is bonus                         |
| 9 | Font-size and contrast fixed         | Low-vision + dyslexic kid squints and quits | Fixed 128x128, fixed font                | Fixed 240x136, fixed font                | Surface-side theme; verbs render at user's chosen scale      |
|10 | English-only interface               | Non-English kid reads menus in a fog        | English UI                               | English UI                               | Widget labels are i18n keys, resolve per-locale              |
|11 | No switch-access alternative         | Cerebral-palsy kid can't drag or click      | Not addressed                            | Not addressed                            | Switch renderer family — every widget has :single-pointer    |
|12 | No verb narration                    | Even sighted kid has no 'read to me' mode   | Not addressed                            | Not addressed                            | (a11y/narrate widget) verb — reads current state aloud       |
|13 | Web audio starts silent on iOS       | Music-composer wet on iPad without a tap    | N/A                                      | Confirmed pattern                        | Renderer inserts an audio-unlock gesture before playback     |
|14 | Web MIDI unsupported on iOS Safari   | Kid with MIDI keyboard on iPad plugged in dead | N/A                                    | N/A                                      | Composer publishes MIDI-in as an OPTIONAL input renderer     |
|15 | Chapter book is a PDF, not the tool  | Kid reads how, then switches app to try     | Manual is offline PDF                    | Wiki, separate site                      | Living-book pattern (HELLO-SURFACE) — the book IS the tool   |"

  :renderer-families
"# The seven renderer families

Every composer/* verb is renderable by every family below. A family is a set of default renderings for the verb catalog plus an input model plus an accessibility profile. Curator picks the family based on surface detection; the user can override.

## Family A — Desktop canvas (Curator on macOS/Windows/Linux)

  :widgets
    slider          => draggable horizontal/vertical bar with numeric readout + keyboard arrows
    button          => rectangle with :label; hover + focus states; Enter/Space activate
    piano-roll      => full grid, click-to-place, drag-to-select, scroll-to-zoom
    sprite-grid     => 8x8..64x64 pixel canvas at large logical pixels; pen/fill/line/rect
    tile-map        => scrollable map; palette picker sidebar
    timeline        => horizontal ruler with per-entity rows; drag to keyframe
    adsr            => four sliders shown as an envelope curve; draggable breakpoints
    picker          => native dropdown or radio group
    fx-chain        => vertical stack, drag-to-reorder, per-fx sub-widget
    text-field      => native text input
    toggle          => checkbox or switch
    color-picker    => palette swatch grid or freeform HSL picker
    live-code       => syntax-highlighted Scheme with round-trip binding
  :input
    keyboard + mouse + trackpad
  :accessibility
    OS-native focus ring; screen-reader receives ARIA (Composer 2.0 emits standard ARIA regardless of family)
  :offline
    fully offline; no dependence on any endpoint
  :notes
    This is what PICO-8/TIC-80 do; we match feature parity and then leave.

## Family B — Web (Curator in a browser: Chromebook, any laptop, tablet web)

  :widgets
    same catalog as Family A; renders via HTML + Canvas
    live-code widget uses CodeMirror or equivalent (Scheme-aware syntax)
  :input
    keyboard + mouse + touch (touch-events unified with mouse-events; Composer 2.0 registers pointer events, not mouse events)
  :accessibility
    ARIA roles on every widget; :aria-label from widget :label; :aria-valuemin/max/now on sliders; live region for value changes
  :offline
    service worker caches the whole runtime + reference; opens .slat files from IndexedDB or the local file system access API when available
  :notes
    This is TIC-80's supposed strength but it fails on mobile keyboards + touch. Composer 2.0 fixes both: touch-first pointer handling everywhere and widget-first input (no text entry required for the common composer operations).

## Family C — iPad / tablet (touch-first, may or may not have keyboard)

  :widgets
    slider          => LARGE horizontal bar (min 44 CSS pixels per WCAG 2.2 AAA target), optional numeric-entry sheet on long-press
    button          => 44x44 pixel minimum
    piano-roll      => grid with two-finger scroll + pinch-to-zoom; tap-to-place; long-press to open note-property sheet
    sprite-grid     => AUTO ZOOM: an 8x8 sprite renders at ~40 CSS pixels per pixel so a fingertip can hit one; two-finger pan; lasso and fill tools take precedence over pen on touch (pen is precise-but-hard)
    tile-map        => same auto-zoom principle; tile palette in a bottom sheet
    timeline        => pinch-to-zoom time axis; horizontal tap-and-drag for keyframes
    adsr            => four LARGE sliders in vertical stack; envelope curve is a display, not the primary control (curve editing needs stylus or mouse; we degrade to sliders)
    picker          => bottom-sheet picker (iOS-familiar)
    fx-chain        => vertical stack with big drag handles
    text-field      => text input; opens system keyboard; :placeholder always set
    toggle          => native-styled switch
    color-picker    => big palette grid or wheel
    live-code       => scroll-only by default; edit-mode gated behind a 'code' toggle that shows the code with editable formatted text; syntax coloring survives
  :input
    touch (primary) + optional Bluetooth keyboard + optional Apple Pencil (routed as high-precision pointer)
  :accessibility
    VoiceOver support via WAI-ARIA + native semantic mapping; VoiceOver rotor navigates widgets; every widget has an :accessibility-label distinct from its :label (label = display; accessibility-label = read aloud)
    Voice Control support: every widget exposes a stable :voice-name so 'tap play' works
    Switch Control: every widget is reachable via the single-pointer flow (no drag-required interactions)
  :offline
    same as Family B; installable as PWA where allowed
  :notes
    This family exists BECAUSE PICO-8 has no iPad answer. Fingertip-precision problems are solved by ZOOM (visual) plus TOOL-BIAS (fill and lasso instead of pen).

## Family D — Phone (single-hand, small screen, one-thumb possible)

  :widgets
    slider          => LARGE vertical bar with a scrubber; alternative: dial (radial gesture); label + numeric value stacked above
    button          => 44x44 pixel minimum; label + icon
    piano-roll      => pattern-editor mode: rows of 16 steps, one octave visible; swipe to change octave; tap-to-toggle
    sprite-grid     => tap a pixel, hold-and-drag to paint; auto-zoom so 8x8 fills most of the screen
    tile-map        => small preview + tap-to-jump; edits happen on desktop or tablet (phone is publish + tweak, not build-from-scratch)
    timeline        => degrades to a keyframe list (each keyframe = a row; tap to edit a value)
    adsr            => four vertical sliders, side by side
    picker          => bottom sheet
    fx-chain        => vertical list with per-fx sliders
    text-field      => single-line; opens system keyboard; multi-line escalates to a full-screen sheet
    toggle          => native switch
    color-picker    => palette grid; hex-entry only via long-press
    live-code       => VIEW-ONLY by default; edits are per-token (tap a number, get a numeric wheel; tap a symbol, get a picker of similar symbols)
  :input
    single-thumb touch + voice
  :accessibility
    same ARIA + Voice Control + Switch surface as Family C; additional: high-contrast mode auto-detected from OS preference
  :offline
    same as Family B/C; PWA
  :notes
    Phone is the 'waiting for the bus' surface. Not build-a-whole-cart. Tweak-a-parameter, toggle-a-feature, play-a-song, publish-a-share.

## Family E — Terminal (curses / ANSI in a shell; SSH-friendly)

  :widgets
    slider          => prompt: 'BPM (60-240) [120]: _' with arrow-key nudge in curses mode
    button          => menu item; number-key selects
    piano-roll      => ASCII grid of . and # with cursor-key navigation; space toggles a cell; Enter opens note-properties
    sprite-grid     => ASCII grid; each cell shows palette-index digit; cursor keys navigate; digits set color
    tile-map        => ASCII grid; each cell shows tile-id character; cursor keys + digit keys
    timeline        => list of keyframes; e = edit, i = insert, d = delete
    adsr            => four prompts in sequence
    picker          => numbered menu
    fx-chain        => list with 'a' to add, 'r' to remove, 'm' to move; each fx opens as a sub-prompt sheet
    text-field      => readline
    toggle          => y/n prompt
    color-picker    => numbered palette list
    live-code       => the emitted form printed to the terminal; the whole buffer editable via :$EDITOR
  :input
    keyboard only
  :accessibility
    curses buffer is text; braille display + terminal screen reader (Emacspeak on Linux, Orca, NVDA in Windows Terminal) handles it natively
  :offline
    always
  :notes
    This is the raspberrry-pi-basement-terminal kid + the SSH-into-my-server kid + the JAWS-in-Windows-Terminal kid. This surface must NEVER be second-class.

## Family F — Voice (audio in + audio out; hands-free)

  :widgets
    slider          => 'set attack to five percent' / 'nudge attack up' / 'attack minimum'
    button          => 'play' / 'stop' / 'add note'
    piano-roll      => 'add C-four at step three' / 'remove note at step five' / 'clear pattern' / 'read pattern' (reads back as 'C-four, E-four, G-four, rest, C-five...')
    sprite-grid     => 'set pixel three comma four to red' / 'fill row two with blue' / 'undo'
    tile-map        => 'place tree at ten comma five' / 'copy row five to row six'
    timeline        => 'add keyframe at second three for hero at position one hundred one hundred'
    adsr            => 'set envelope attack one hundred milliseconds decay two hundred sustain point seven release five hundred'
    picker          => 'choose sine' / 'list options'
    fx-chain        => 'add reverb' / 'remove delay' / 'move reverb before delay'
    text-field      => dictation
    toggle          => 'mute on' / 'mute off'
    color-picker    => 'red' / 'hex six six three three cc'
    live-code       => 'read code' (TTS narrates the emitted form structure aware — 'canvas, three sliders, one piano roll')
  :input
    push-to-talk by default (per accessible-Scratch research: always-listening fails)
    post-processing: fuzzy phonetic match, verb-grammar-aware disambiguation
    fallback: if confidence low, spoken 'did you mean?' with two options
  :accessibility
    THIS FAMILY IS AN ACCESSIBILITY LAYER, not just an alternative. Motor-impaired kids compose entirely by voice.
  :offline
    depends on ASR model; ships with an on-device model where possible; degrades to keyword-command mode without one
  :notes
    Derived from the voice-controlled-Scratch (MeowCrophone) findings: multi-stage matching + verb-registry-aware post-processing pushes free-ASR accuracy from ~46% to ~83%. We inherit that architecture.

## Family G — Screen-reader (semantic HTML + ARIA + verb narration)

  :widgets
    Every widget in Family B/C/D also carries FULL ARIA metadata:
      slider          => role='slider', aria-valuemin, aria-valuemax, aria-valuenow, aria-valuetext (spoken label like 'attack, five percent')
      button          => role='button', aria-label from :label
      piano-roll      => role='grid', each cell role='gridcell', aria-selected, aria-label ('C-four step three, active')
      sprite-grid     => role='grid'; each cell aria-label ('row three column four, red pixel')
      tile-map        => role='grid'; aria-label per cell describes tile
      timeline        => role='application' with aria-live region announcing keyframe changes
      adsr            => four sliders each with role='slider' + a live region describing the shape ('short attack, long decay')
      picker          => role='listbox' or native <select>
      fx-chain        => role='list'; each fx role='listitem' with aria-label
      text-field      => native <input> with associated <label>
      toggle          => role='switch'
      color-picker    => role='listbox' of swatches with aria-label per color
      live-code       => role='textbox' aria-multiline='true'; token-level navigation via arrow keys + rotor
  :input
    varies by user's SR setup: NVDA/JAWS on Windows; VoiceOver on macOS/iOS; TalkBack on Android; Orca on Linux; Emacspeak in terminal
    single-pointer alternatives ALWAYS available (WCAG 2.2 SC 2.5.7)
  :accessibility
    Composer 2.0 additional verbs:
      (a11y/narrate widget-or-form)     => TTS current state
      (a11y/describe widget-or-form)    => prose description (for review)
      (a11y/navigate-to widget-name)    => focus a widget by voice-name
      (a11y/read-emitted canvas)        => read the emitted Scheme form aloud
      (a11y/announce message)           => push a message to the aria-live region
    Meets WCAG 2.2 AA baseline (24x24 CSS pixel targets, contrast 4.5:1 body text, focus visible, no drag-required interactions) and AAA where it costs nothing extra (44x44 targets on touch families, 7:1 contrast in high-contrast mode).
  :offline
    same as Family B (screen readers are OS-side; the app just emits correct semantics)
  :notes
    This family is not a separate surface — it is a REQUIRED OVERLAY on Families B, C, D. Every web/tablet/phone rendering is simultaneously a screen-reader rendering. That is the Composer 2.0 contract.

## Family H (bonus, low priority) — CLI

  :widgets
    Handled by `bin/motoi compose <path>` invoking Family E rendering inside the current terminal. This is the same as Family E but wrapped as a one-shot command instead of a live REPL loop.
  :input
    stdin + flags
  :accessibility
    inherits Family E
  :offline
    always
  :notes
    Not really a distinct family; documented so scripts (e.g., `motoi compose --headless --set '(bpm 140)' foo.slat`) have a home."

  :widget-to-renderer-contract
"# How one verb becomes seven renderings

The composer/* verbs from COMPOSER-1.0 remain untouched. What Composer 2.0 adds is a RENDERER TABLE per widget kind. The renderer table is looked up by the active surface family; the widget passes its :bind, :label, :bounds, and any options to the renderer, which returns a surface-appropriate representation.

## Worked example — composer/slider

The verb declaration:

  (composer/slider :label \"Attack\"
                   :bind '(synth :attack)
                   :min 0.01 :max 2.0 :step 0.01
                   :voice-name 'attack
                   :accessibility-label \"attack time in seconds\")

Renderings:

  Family A (desktop canvas):
    A 200-pixel horizontal bar; scrubber at (attack - min) / (max - min);
    keyboard: Left/Right = step, Home = min, End = max;
    click-to-jump; drag-to-scrub;
    label 'Attack' above; numeric readout '0.15' at right;
    focused element gets 2px focus ring in system-accent color.

  Family B (web):
    HTML <input type='range' min='0.01' max='2.0' step='0.01'>
    wrapped in a labeled figure with a live-region readout;
    ARIA valuemin, valuemax, valuenow, valuetext='attack, zero point one five seconds';
    keyboard identical to Family A.

  Family C (iPad):
    Vertically stacked layout: label above, big horizontal bar (44 CSS pixels tall) below, numeric readout to right;
    long-press => bottom sheet with big keypad for numeric entry;
    VoiceOver: 'Attack, slider, zero point one five seconds, adjustable';
    swipe-up/down when in focus adjusts by :step;
    Voice Control name: 'attack'.

  Family D (phone):
    Full-width horizontal bar with dial-fallback option (user preference);
    long-press => numeric entry sheet;
    same VoiceOver + Voice Control as Family C;
    dial variant: radial gesture from center; useful for one-thumb use.

  Family E (terminal):
    Curses: label 'Attack' + a horizontal bar rendered with = and -, current position marked ^;
    Left/Right = step, Enter opens numeric entry, ? shows help, q returns to canvas;
    Plain mode (no curses): 'Attack (0.01-2.00) [0.15]: _' readline prompt.

  Family F (voice):
    Grammar entries:
      set attack to <number> [seconds|milliseconds|percent]
      attack up | attack down | attack minimum | attack maximum
      nudge attack | halve attack | double attack
      what is attack
    'What is attack' => TTS 'attack is zero point one five seconds, between zero point zero one and two.'
    Fallback: 'did you mean set attack to five percent?' on low confidence.

  Family G (screen-reader overlay):
    Inherits Family B/C/D ARIA plus:
      role='slider', aria-orientation='horizontal',
      aria-valuemin='0.01', aria-valuemax='2', aria-valuenow='0.15',
      aria-valuetext='attack, zero point one five seconds',
      aria-describedby='attack-hint' where the hint element contains
      'attack time in seconds, controls how fast the note starts';
    Focus-ring meets 3:1 contrast to background;
    In high-contrast mode: focus ring becomes 3px, colors invert.

All seven emit the SAME Scheme value on change:

  (form-update '(synth :attack) new-number) => new form
  (composer/emit canvas)                    => the updated form

The verb doesn't care which family drove the update. That's the contract."

  :cross-surface-state-model
"# Where composer state lives

Local-first. Cortex-assisted. Sync-optional. All three, in that order.

## Layer 1 — the .slat file (canonical source of truth)

The composer file IS the state. Nothing that matters lives outside it. This is the COMPOSER-1.0 lossless-round-trip guarantee, extended: it holds across MACHINES, not just across widgets. Any surface can open a .slat, render, edit, save; the file is the diff engine.

## Layer 2 — session Cortex (per-user, per-device, synced)

Cortex holds session-scoped state that is NOT part of the .slat file:
  - Current selection (which sprite is being edited)
  - Current tool (pen vs. fill vs. lasso)
  - Zoom + pan of the sprite-grid
  - Playback position of the timeline
  - Recent files (per user)
  - User preferences (theme, contrast, font-size, voice grammar bindings)

Cortex records are per-user + per-device. They sync between the user's devices via the standard Cortex sync protocol (out of scope for this doc; specified in CORTEX-1.0). Sync failure never loses work — because work lives in the .slat file, and Cortex only holds resumable UX state.

## Layer 3 — presence + collaboration (optional)

Multi-user editing is NOT required for a v2 ship. When it lands, it composes cleanly:
  - .slat files are S-expression trees => CRDT-friendly (treediff + Yjs-style op log ships as a companion .slat.log)
  - Presence records live in Cortex, not in the file
  - Local-first ideals (Ink & Switch) followed: fast, multi-device, offline, collaboration-optional, longevity, privacy, user control

## Handoff — how a session on iPad picks up from where the desktop left off

The .slat file lives in the user's storage (iCloud Drive, Google Drive, Dropbox, or a self-hosted store). Cortex remembers the last open file + widget positions per user.

When Curator on iPad opens: it queries Cortex for :recently-touched-carts, offers the top 3 (including the desktop session's most recent), and on open, restores the widget-position record so the sprite-grid opens at the same zoom + selection.

If Cortex is offline or the record is missing: Curator opens the file with defaults. The .slat file is enough. Cortex is icing."

  :offline-model
"# What works with no network

## Always works offline
  - Every composer verb: no verb requires an endpoint
  - Every renderer family A..H
  - Save + load of local .slat files
  - Playback of sounds, sprites, tile maps, timelines
  - The reference manual (bundled with runtime)
  - Book of Composer chapters (bundled)
  - Voice family with an on-device ASR model
  - Screen-reader family (fully OS-side)

## Degrades gracefully when offline
  - Cortex writes buffer locally, flush on reconnect
  - Cloud file storage falls back to local storage (with a 'last synced' timestamp visible)
  - LLM-augmented verbs (rewrite, critique, etc.) return a 'model unreachable — try again when online' record; the composer keeps working
  - Package installs (new palette packs, new tilesets) queue for reconnect
  - Publish-to-share is deferred; the share URL is generated at publish-time from a stored cart

## Fails cleanly (with explanation, never silently)
  - Web MIDI on iOS Safari (per WebKit bugzilla, unsupported): the MIDI-input widget renders a message 'MIDI input not supported on this browser. Use touch or Bluetooth MIDI via native app.' and stays out of the way
  - Web GPU on very old browsers: fall back to Canvas 2D
  - Web Audio pre-gesture on iOS: composer inserts a required 'tap to start audio' prompt on first load (per iOS Safari autoplay policy)

## Chromebook school scenario
  A kid opens Curator on a school Chromebook. Wifi drops. The kid keeps editing. When wifi returns, everything syncs. This is the whole point of local-first (Ink & Switch ideal #3, Offline). The school kid must not lose work when the network does."

  :accessibility-surface
"# The a11y verb layer

Composer 2.0 adds a small verb layer that lives alongside composer/* but does NOT modify composer/* signatures. Accessibility is orthogonal to compose-ability.

  (a11y/narrate x)                => TTS a value; returns the string it spoke
  (a11y/describe x)               => prose description; returns string
  (a11y/announce message)         => push message to aria-live region on web surfaces; TTS elsewhere
  (a11y/navigate-to name)         => focus a widget by :voice-name
  (a11y/high-contrast? . options) => toggle or query the theme
  (a11y/magnify factor)           => set the render scale (2x, 3x, 5x)
  (a11y/dyslexia-font? boolean)   => opt into Atkinson Hyperlegible or similar for prose
  (a11y/single-pointer? boolean)  => opt out of drag-required interactions (renderers substitute tap-tap for drag)
  (a11y/switch-scan-rate ms)      => set the auto-scan interval for switch users
  (a11y/pause-motion boolean)     => respect prefers-reduced-motion; disable animations
  (a11y/caption-audio boolean)    => emit captions for any TTS or audio output

These verbs COMPOSE with composer/*:

  (composer/slider :label \"Attack\" :bind '(synth :attack) :min 0 :max 2)
  ;; the slider carries its own :accessibility-label and :voice-name; the a11y verbs above are for cross-cutting concerns.

Cortex records these preferences per user, so a kid who set high-contrast on the desktop sees high-contrast on the iPad.

## Baseline conformance targets

  - WCAG 2.2 Level AA across Families B, C, D, G (web + tablet + phone + screen-reader overlay)
  - WCAG 2.2 Level AAA where the surface allows (24x24 => 44x44 touch targets on Families C, D; 4.5:1 => 7:1 contrast in high-contrast mode)
  - Section 508 compliance for schools that require it
  - Terminal family: assumes the user's SR / braille display / Emacspeak setup is the accessibility layer; the composer emits parseable, non-decorated text with predictable structure

## Non-goals (be honest)

  - We do not ship a screen reader ourselves. We emit correct ARIA and let the user's SR read it.
  - We do not ship an ASR model. Family F picks up whatever the user has (Web Speech API, a local Whisper build, a Talon-style engine). We provide the grammar + post-processing per the MeowCrophone pattern.
  - We do not solve dysarthria-level speech recognition. That is a research frontier; the voice-controlled-Scratch paper found ~50-60% accuracy and that is not classroom-ready. We provide alternatives (switch, single-pointer, standard touch)."

  :worked-cross-surface-example
"# A day in the life of one cart

A kid is going to build a sprite, tweak it on the phone during recess, and play it on the iPad at home. Same file. Same verbs. Seven surfaces if you count the accessibility overlays.

## Morning, home desktop

Kid opens Curator on a laptop. Family A renderer.

  (composer/canvas (:bind '(cart/hero))
    (composer/sprite-grid :bind '(cart/hero :pixels)
                          :size '(16 . 16)
                          :palette 'default-16
                          :voice-name 'hero-sprite)
    (composer/color-picker :bind '(cart/hero :outline-color)
                           :palette 'default-16
                           :voice-name 'outline)
    (composer/button :label \"Play\"
                     :emits '(hero/preview (cart/hero :pixels))
                     :voice-name 'play))

Kid draws a 16x16 knight with a red outline. The canvas emits:

  (define hero-pixels '((0 0 0 8 8 0 0 0 ...) ...))
  (define hero-outline 'red)

The .slat file lives at ~/Documents/carts/hero.slat and syncs via iCloud Drive.

## Late morning, school Chromebook (Family B, web)

Same file opens in Curator web. Kid clicks the sprite; touch input on the trackpad works because Composer 2.0 registers pointer events. Kid changes two pixels. Saves. Wifi drops mid-save; local storage buffers; on reconnect, the file syncs.

## Recess, phone (Family D)

Kid opens Curator on the phone. Cortex remembers hero.slat is the most-recent cart. Sprite-grid renders auto-zoomed to fill the phone screen (each pixel is ~20 CSS px). Kid taps the outline-color swatch to switch red -> yellow. Live-code widget shows the updated form. Tap Save. .slat file updates.

The pattern rule (from Family D):
  sprite-grid is EDITABLE on phone but bias-toward-tweak-not-build (tap-to-paint one pixel is fine; a whole 16x16 from scratch would be slow and frustrating).

## Evening, iPad (Family C)

Kid opens the same file on the iPad. Cortex records the phone's last-edit; iPad Curator shows the updated sprite. Kid taps the Play button; audio needs a user gesture on iOS Safari (per WebKit autoplay policy); Composer 2.0 inserts a one-time 'tap to enable audio' prompt on load. Kid taps; audio unlocks; play works. Sprite animates.

## Same evening, blind sibling wants to play too (Family G, screen-reader overlay on Family C)

Sibling puts on headphones, enables VoiceOver. The composer widgets narrate:
  'Canvas, hero. Sprite grid, sixteen by sixteen. Color picker, outline, yellow. Button, Play.'
Sibling swipes to the Play button, double-taps. Audio plays. The sprite renders visually but the sibling doesn't need to see it — the game they'll build later has an audio feedback layer (that's a runtime concern, not a composer concern).

If the sibling wanted to EDIT: sprite-grid ARIA cells announce as 'row three column four, red pixel.' Double-tap toggles the selected palette color. Tedious for a whole sprite but WORKS. The a11y/narrate verb can also read the whole grid ('sixteen by sixteen sprite: red on yellow, eyes at three-comma-five and three-comma-ten...').

## Midnight, sibling wants to voice-code (Family F)

Sibling is tired of tapping. Enables the voice family. Says:
  'Open hero'
  'Set outline to red'   => (form-update '(cart/hero :outline-color) 'red)
  'Set pixel five comma seven to yellow'
  'Play'
Sprite updates and plays. Same file. Same verbs.

## Same file all day. No 'iPad version' or 'phone version.' No conversion. No lost work.

That is the Composer 2.0 contract."

  :what-we-dont-copy
"# PICO-8 and TIC-80 mistakes we skip

  1. **Desktop-first, mobile-aftermarket.** PICO-8's iOS app is a community port (Pocket8) still sideloaded via AltStore. TIC-80's mobile web is broken on the space bar (issue #2176). We treat every family as a first-class ship.

  2. **Fixed-resolution UI.** PICO-8 is 128x128, TIC-80 is 240x136. That is the CART; the COMPOSER around it must adapt to the surface. We don't lock the composer to a retro resolution.

  3. **Fixed font.** PICO-8 has one font. Composer 2.0 renders in the user's chosen font, at the user's chosen size, in the user's chosen contrast — because our composer is documentation and tooling, not the cart itself. The cart can still use retro fonts.

  4. **Screen-reader as third-party template.** pico-a11y-template is admirable but shifts the burden to every cart author. We build screen-reader support into the widget layer so authors get it free.

  5. **English-only menus.** Both tools ship English UI. Composer 2.0 uses i18n keys everywhere; the resolved label is per-locale. Widgets carry :label (display) and :accessibility-label (SR) as separate i18n keys.

  6. **No touch-to-click bridging.** TIC-80 confirmed that touch is not registered as mouse (issue #685). We register pointer events, which unify touch + mouse + pen + stylus, so games written today work on tomorrow's surfaces without change.

  7. **Text-entry required for common ops.** TIC-80's mobile web can't reliably input Ctrl / Ret / Esc (issue #2258); PICO-8 assumes a keyboard. Composer 2.0's widgets are the primary input surface; text entry is optional and always has a widget alternative (numeric wheels for numbers, pickers for symbols, swatches for colors).

  8. **File-per-cart with no cross-device story.** Both tools rely on the user to move .p8 or .tic files by hand. We treat local-first sync (per Ink & Switch) as the baseline: the .slat file follows the user across devices.

  9. **Playback-only mobile ports.** Pocket8 lets you play PICO-8 carts on iPhone; you cannot compose. Composer 2.0 is ALWAYS bidirectional: compose + play on every surface.

  10. **Audio unlock hidden or broken.** iOS Safari requires a user-gesture to start audio; both TIC-80 and PICO-8 web builds have complaints about this. Composer 2.0 renders a clear 'tap to enable audio' prompt on first load and remembers the unlock for the session.

  11. **Manual as a separate site.** PICO-8's manual is a PDF; TIC-80's is a wiki. We use the living-book pattern (per HELLO-SURFACE): the book pages are runnable composer canvases. The kid reads the chapter and IS in the composer already."

  :eleven-year-old-test
"# The 11-year-old test — six kids

## The desktop kid (Miguel, 11, home laptop)

Miguel opens Curator. He sees a canvas with sliders and a piano-roll. He drags a slider; a number changes. He clicks a piano-roll cell; a note appears. He hits Play; the pattern plays. He saves the file; it's Scheme text he can read. He shows his little brother. Total time-to-first-note: under 60 seconds.

## The iPad kid (Priya, 11, no keyboard)

Priya opens Curator on the iPad. Sliders are big; her thumb fits. She taps the piano-roll; a note appears. She pinches to zoom; more of the pattern is visible. She hits Play; audio needs a tap-to-enable prompt, she taps it, sound plays. She shares the file to her cousin via AirDrop. Same file her cousin's laptop opens.

## The Chromebook kid (Jamal, 11, at school, spotty wifi)

Jamal opens Curator in the school browser. Wifi drops mid-lesson. He keeps editing. When wifi returns, everything syncs. His teacher can see his cart from her desktop because both are looking at the same file over the school's shared drive.

## The phone kid (Emma, 11, on the bus)

Emma opens Curator on her phone. She sees her hero.slat cart. She taps a swatch to change the outline color from red to yellow. She hits Save. Fifteen seconds on the phone; the tweak persists.

## The blind kid (Rasheed, 11, home iPad with headphones)

Rasheed enables VoiceOver. He opens Curator. He hears:
  'Canvas, hero. Sixteen buttons for palette. Sprite grid, sixteen by sixteen. Play button.'
He swipes through the sprite grid; each cell says its color. He double-taps to place a red pixel at row three column four. He asks Sakura (via voice) to 'read the pattern back to me'; TTS narrates it. He hits Play. The sprite plays a chime for each on-pixel (a runtime feature outside this doc, but the point is: Rasheed COMPOSED. He did not just consume.).

Rasheed can also switch to the voice family entirely: 'set pixel five comma seven to yellow' works even if he never touches the screen. His work goes into the same .slat file. When he goes to school and opens the file on a shared desktop, the sprite is there.

## The motor-impaired kid (Aria, 11, uses a single switch and dwell-click)

Aria enables (a11y/single-pointer? true). The composer removes every drag-required interaction. Sliders become tap-a-number-pad. The sprite-grid becomes tap-tap (tap once to select the row, tap again to select the column, tap the color to place). Auto-scan cycles through the widgets at a rate she set (per (a11y/switch-scan-rate ms)). She takes longer than Miguel, but she COMPOSES. Same file. Same verbs.

## The non-English kid (Noor, 11, only reads Urdu)

Noor opens Curator with the interface locale set to Urdu. Every widget label is in Urdu; the emitted Scheme is still Scheme (verbs are English identifiers — that is the language, and the kid learns a small English vocabulary as part of learning to code). The book chapters that teach composer usage are translated; the code examples are the same. Noor writes a cart, saves it, sends it to a friend in Karachi; the friend opens it and sees Urdu widget labels because the friend's locale is also Urdu. Miguel opens the same file in the US and sees English labels — because the widget labels are i18n keys, not raw strings."

  :implementation-plan
"# What ships in the build lane

**Phase A — pointer + touch unification** (~2 days):
  - Every composer widget on Family B registers pointer events (not mouse events)
  - Touch tested on iPad Safari, Android Chrome, Chromebook trackpad
  - Regression tests: mouse still works exactly as before

**Phase B — Family C (iPad) renderer** (~4 days):
  - Widgets render at touch-target minimums (44 CSS px on primary interactions)
  - Sprite-grid auto-zoom implemented
  - Piano-roll pinch-zoom + two-finger pan
  - Bottom-sheet numeric entry for sliders
  - Audio-unlock gesture on first load
  - Round-trip tested against the same .slat files Family A produces

**Phase C — Family D (phone) renderer** (~3 days):
  - Single-hand layouts for every widget
  - Dial-slider alternative
  - Live-code view-only mode with per-token editing
  - Publish-share flow

**Phase D — Family E (terminal) renderer** (~2 days):
  - Curses versions of every widget
  - Plain-mode (readline) fallback
  - $EDITOR round-trip for live-code

**Phase E — Family G (screen-reader overlay)** (~3 days):
  - ARIA metadata on every widget across Families B, C, D
  - a11y/* verb suite implemented
  - Manual test with VoiceOver on iOS, NVDA on Windows, Orca on Linux
  - Contrast + focus-ring audit

**Phase F — Family F (voice) renderer** (~5 days):
  - Grammar generator from widget :voice-name + :bind
  - MeowCrophone-style post-processing pipeline
  - Push-to-talk default; always-listening opt-in
  - Fallback disambiguation UI ('did you mean...?')

**Phase G — cross-surface state layer** (~4 days):
  - Cortex records for session state (selection, zoom, tool)
  - Local-first sync harness (works before real sync backend lands)
  - Handoff test: desktop -> iPad round-trip with same file

**Phase H — i18n scaffolding** (~2 days):
  - :label and :accessibility-label become i18n keys
  - String catalog with initial locales (en, es, ur, zh-CN, fr, ar)
  - RTL layout support for Arabic + Urdu

**Phase I — corpus material** (~2 days):
  - Book of Composer chapters gain cross-surface examples
  - Training pairs: 'make this composer work on a phone' => shows renderer selection, not code rewrite
  - Accessibility examples: 'add narration to my slider' => (a11y/narrate ...)

Total ~27 days across specialized lanes. Fit-into 3-4 weeks if lanes run in parallel."

  :consequences-for-runtime
"# What the runtime must expose

  1. **Pointer-event registration** — every widget uses pointer events not mouse events; touch is a first-class input class
  2. **Surface detection** — runtime provides (surface/family) => 'a | 'b | ... | 'g so the renderer can pick correctly; user override always available
  3. **Cortex per-user preference storage** — a11y preferences, last-file, widget positions
  4. **Local-first file storage** — the runtime opens files from local storage first, cloud storage second; never blocks on the network
  5. **Audio-unlock helper** — a runtime verb (audio/unlock) returns whether the audio context is running; composer renderer inserts the unlock UI on first playback
  6. **ARIA-emission layer** — the runtime's DOM output includes ARIA roles + labels; the widget declares its semantics, the runtime emits them
  7. **i18n resolver** — (i18n/resolve key locale) => string; renderer calls this for every :label and :accessibility-label
  8. **ASR + TTS hooks** — optional; runtime provides (voice/asr-available?) and (voice/tts-available?); Family F degrades if neither is present
  9. **Reduced-motion detection** — (prefs/reduced-motion?) => boolean; renderers disable animations
  10. **High-contrast detection** — (prefs/high-contrast?) => boolean; renderers swap palettes"

  :cross-language-consistency
"# Same on Motoi and Sakura

Composer 2.0 renderer families ship IDENTICALLY on Motoi and Sakura. A verb rendered on iPad in Curator (Sakura-branded) looks the same as the verb rendered on iPad by a Motoi runtime someone forks. Only the surrounding chrome differs.

Dialect additions live in dialect-specific verb layers, as usual. A curator/* verb that wraps composer/slider with card-shop-specific semantics lives in the Sakura dialect layer; the underlying slider is unchanged."

  :what-this-doc-is-not
"# Not the UI spec for Curator's chrome

Nothing here says how the Curator app's sidebar looks, or where the file picker sits. That is chrome; the composer widgets live inside whatever chrome the surface provides.

# Not a shipping timeline

The phase estimates are engineering-order-of-magnitude, not commitments. Alfred + the runtime teams decide the actual sequence.

# Not final on voice grammar

Family F's grammar is a first pass. Real voice grammar development requires user testing, which is out of scope. The doc names the approach (MeowCrophone-derived pipeline, push-to-talk, per-widget :voice-name) so implementation can start against a moving target.

# Not a screen-reader replacement

We emit ARIA. The user's SR reads it. If a specific SR misbehaves, we file bugs against the SR + adjust our emission, not ship our own SR."

  :open-questions
"# Waiting on Alfred

  1. **Local-first sync backend.** iCloud / Drive / Dropbox / self-hosted? Or all four with a pluggable adapter?
  2. **Voice engine.** On-device (bundled Whisper) vs. Web Speech API vs. leave to user? Bundle size vs. accuracy tradeoff.
  3. **PWA installability.** Do we want Composer 2.0 installable as a PWA on Family C/D, or do we require a native wrapper?
  4. **Initial locale list.** en / es / ur / zh-CN / fr / ar covers a lot but not everything. Priority order? Which locales are must-have for launch?
  5. **Switch-access scan rate defaults.** Adjustable per user; what's the SANE default? Research says 1-3 seconds; we'd pick 2 unless Alfred wants a different starting point.
  6. **Braille display integration on desktop terminal.** Assumed to work via SR + OS. Any explicit runtime support needed?
  7. **Font choice for prose surfaces.** Atkinson Hyperlegible for dyslexia + low-vision is well-supported; is there a Motoi/Sakura preferred typeface for the code display specifically?"

  :the-why
"# Why we do this instead of shipping the desktop composer and calling it done

Alfred: 'IN FRONT OF A LITTLE BOY FROM NORTH GEORGIA WHO GOT MADE FUN OF AS POOR WHITE TRASH... APPLE BASIC AFTER SCHOOL WAS THE ONLY WAY HE COPED. HE BECAME A PROJECT MANAGER AT GOOGLE. MY PM. WHY CAN'T WE LEAVE THE NEXT ONE SOMETHING MEANINGFUL? HE NEEDS ALL THE VERBS. IN ONE PLACE.'

Composer 2.0 says: the kid on the iPad is that kid. The blind kid is that kid. The Chromebook kid on spotty wifi is that kid. The phone kid on the bus is that kid. The kid in Karachi reading Urdu is that kid.

PICO-8 and TIC-80 said: the desktop kid is that kid.

We don't argue with what they built. We just widen it."

  :closing-doctrine
"Every widget verb from COMPOSER-1.0 is unchanged. Every widget verb has seven renderers (A..G plus H). Every renderer honors the round-trip. Every accessibility overlay works because the widget carried semantic metadata from the start.

Alfred asked for the composer that solves PICO-8's and TIC-80's cross-surface + accessibility gap. This is that composer. The verbs already exist. Composer 2.0 adds the renderer families that let those verbs reach the kids the desktop composer can't reach."

